History: Ursa Major is one of the 88 modern constellations and has been recognized since ancient times. Its name comes from the Latin word for "bear".
Cultural Significance: In Greek mythology, it represents the bear that Zeus saved from the sun. Native American tribes used it for navigation in the northern hemisphere.
Notable Features: The constellation contains the Big Dipper (a group of seven stars). The North Star (Polaris) lies near the end of the Big Dipper's handle. Ursa Major is the largest constellation in the sky.

Cassiopeia
History: Cassiopeia is one of the 88 modern constellations and was first described by Ptolemy. Its name comes from the Greek myth of the queen Cassiopeia.
Cultural Significance: In Greek mythology, Cassiopeia was transformed into a constellation after boasting about her beauty. Ancient navigators used it for orientation in the northern hemisphere.
Notable Features: Cassiopeia forms a distinctive 'W' pattern with five bright stars. It is located near the North Star and is easily visible from the Northern Hemisphere. The brightest star in Cassiopeia is Schedar.

